HEADWORD: Rumple
<hw>Rum"ple</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Rumpled</conjf> <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rumpling</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
<ets>rimple</ets>, and D. <ets>rimpelen</ets> to wrinkle,
<ets>rompelig</ets> rough, uneven, G. <ets>r⟦uum⟧mpfen</ets> to wrinkle,
MHG. <ets>r⟦uum⟧mphen</ets>, OHG. <ets>rimpfan</ets>, Gr.
<grk>"ra`mfos</grk> the crooked beak of birds of prey, <?/ to
roam.]</ety> <def>To make uneven; to form into irregular inequalities;
to wrinkle; to crumple; <as>as, to <ex>rumple</ex> an apron or a
cravat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They would not give a dog's ear of their most <qex>rumpled</qex>
and ragged Scotch paper for twenty of your fairest assignats.</q>
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rumple</ent>⟦br⟧

